=========================================
std::make_unique (C++14) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::make_unique?
----------------------------
• Introduced in C++14.
• A utility function that creates an object and returns a std::unique_ptr.
• It allocates memory and transfers ownership to unique_ptr in one step.
• Recommended way to create unique_ptr objects in modern C++.

Header:
#include <memory>

--------------------------------------------------

2. Why was std::make_unique introduced?
---------------------------------------

Before C++14:

std::unique_ptr<Employee> ptr(new Employee());

Problems:
✔ Explicit use of `new`
✔ More verbose
✔ Less exception-safe in complex expressions
✔ Modern C++ discourages direct use of `new`

C++14 introduced:

auto ptr = std::make_unique<Employee>();

Benefits:
✔ Cleaner
✔ Safer
✔ Easier to read
✔ Modern C++ best practice

--------------------------------------------------

3. How does std::make_unique work?
----------------------------------

It performs two operations together:

1. Allocates memory.
2. Immediately wraps the object inside a std::unique_ptr.

Example:

auto emp = std::make_unique<Employee>("John", 30);

Conceptually equivalent to:

std::unique_ptr<Employee>(
    new Employee("John",30)
);

--------------------------------------------------

4. Why is it Better than using new?
-----------------------------------

Instead of

std::unique_ptr<Employee> p(new Employee());

write

auto p = std::make_unique<Employee>();

Advantages:

✔ No explicit `new`
✔ Immediate ownership transfer
✔ Cleaner syntax
✔ Better exception safety
✔ Follows RAII

--------------------------------------------------

5. Exception Safety (MOST IMPORTANT)
------------------------------------

Problem:

foo(std::unique_ptr<Employee>(new Employee()), bar());

If an exception occurs while evaluating the function arguments, writing code
with explicit `new` is more error-prone.

Preferred:

foo(std::make_unique<Employee>(), bar());

The object is created and immediately owned by unique_ptr in one step,
making the code safer and easier to write correctly.

--------------------------------------------------

6. When should you use std::make_unique?
----------------------------------------

✔ When an object has a single owner.
✔ Whenever you need a std::unique_ptr.
✔ In factory functions.
✔ When returning std::unique_ptr from functions.
✔ Preferred way to dynamically allocate objects in modern C++.

Avoid:

✘ If ownership needs to be shared.
Use std::make_shared() instead.

--------------------------------------------------

7. Arrays
---------

auto arr = std::make_unique<int[]>(10);

Equivalent to:

std::unique_ptr<int[]> arr(new int[10]);

--------------------------------------------------

8. make_unique vs make_shared
-----------------------------

make_unique
------------
• Returns std::unique_ptr
• Single owner
• No reference counting
• Lower overhead

make_shared
------------
• Returns std::shared_ptr
• Multiple owners
• Uses reference counting
• Higher overhead

--------------------------------------------------

